        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The individual components have linewidths of 1-2km/s and we therefore ask for a velocity resolution of ~0.3km/s to sample the lines. This resolution is achieved with the 468.7MHz wide bandwidth correlator setting (dual pol), which corresponds to ~500km/s. The absorption line complex spans the 520-650km/s range which comfortably fits. The extra continuum channels will be very useful however, as an adequate continuum subtraction is key to the experiment. This may require higher order polynomial fits for which large line-free frequency ranges are required.

Note that we shift the central velocity of the source away from systemic velocity such that it falls in the middle of the absorption line velocity range. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We select the highest angular resolution in Band 6 of 0.03". This is required in order to resolve the core/jet structure in the AGN of Cen A to 30mas, or ~0.6pc. According to Tingay et al. (1998), the inner jet has a length of ~60mas. We will thus be able to distinguish between absorption towards the central core and absorption against the innermost, newly launched northern jet that is beamed towards us.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The continuum flux in the center of CenA will be resolved into a core and a jet component. 
At cm wavelengths the core is dominating the jet by a factor of ~4 and we expect that the spectral indices of both components are roughly flat between cm and mm wavelengths. For a total 1mm flux density of ~6Jy, we therefore expect ~1-2Jy in the jet. The continuum is therefore not the limiting factor for our sensitivity estimate. 

In our 2011.0.00010.S cycle 0 data we measure an optical depth of HCO+ and HCN (1-0) in both, "narrow" and "broad" lines. The faintest lines are the "broad" HCN lines with typical optical depths of ~0.05. 
From our data and from Israel et al. (2014) we can assume that the medium exhibits a temperature of ~50K, an H2 volume density of ~10^4.5 and a 10^15 cm^-2 HCO+ and HCN column density. A Large Velocity Gradient (LVG) radiative transfer prediction for such gas is that the (3-2) lines are about 2/3 the brightness temperature of the (1-0) lines. This corresponds to a typical tau of 0.03. For a S/N of 10 against a 1 Jy background flux, we thus require a tau rms of 0.003 or 3mJy.

The individual components have linewidths of 1-2km/s and we therefore ask for a velocity resolution of ~0.3km/s for good sampling. 

Dynamic range considerations: The core of CenA has a flux density of ~6Jy at 1mm wavelengths. The continuum jet/core flux ratio is about of order a few, well within the typical ALMA dynamic range of ~100. The AGN is also adequate for self-calibration, which will increase the dynamic range
further. Although the emission lines are much fainter than the continuum, the self-calibrated noise from our Cycle 0 data shows thermal behavior and we expect that Cycle 3 data will be even better, given the much improved uv-coverage. In addition, we will subtract the continuum before deriving the absorption spectrum, which eliminates the influence of the strong continuum core almost completely.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We require two basebands for the continuum. The two spectral line basebands require ~0.3km/s resolution for the absorption features, but also a very large bandwidth to potentially fit higher polynomials to determine an adequate baseline for the very bright source.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
