        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The circumnuclear disk extends across ~500km/s. In addition, we expect a velocity dispersion increase in the sphere of influence up to 600km/s. We thus require &gt;1000km/s bandwidth, and the next available correaltor mode is ~2000km/s. A good coverage of line-free channels is also important for the best continuum subtraction of the bright AGN core and jet. We may need to fit higher order polynomials and the 1.875GHz bandwidth mode will allow us to do so. 

The same mode will provide us with a channel spacing of ~1km/s. This will be very well suited to resolve the linewidths of clumps, in case we will find the clumps that are similar to those in absorption, or clumps similar to those in the Milky Way. For clumps with wider lines, we may slightly smooth the data. We would, however, like to retain the 1km/s of this correlator mode for the observations.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In Science goal "Hires-Absorption" we ask for a resolution of 0.03". The rms of these observations (57K) won't be sensitive enough to pick up emission at high S/N. So in this "Medres-Emission" science goal, we ask for a low enough resolution to guarantee a detection in emission at the same time as being high enough to probe the environment as close to the AGN as possible. The observations at 0.2" (4pc) will provide many beams across the 1.4" sphere of influence. 

The largest angular scale can be set by the size of the nuclear disk, 2.5". No ACA is required for this value.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In our cycle 0 data (2011.0.00010.S), we measure linewidths of ~30 km/s for clumps with a peak near the absorption feature of ~0.4K for HCN (HCO+ is a factor of 2 brighter). The peak may be artifical due to the influence of the absorption, or may be real, but it is a representative value for an expected sensitivity estimate. 

From our data and from Israel et al. (2014) we can assume that the medium exhibits a temperature of ~50K, an H2 volume density of ~10^4.5 and a 10^15 cm^-2 HCO+ and HCN column density. A Large Velocity Gradient (LVG) radiative transfer prediction for such gas is that the (3-2) lines are about 2/3 the brightness temperature of the (1-0) lines. This corresponds to a value of 0.3K for the HCN(3-2). 

The requested 0.2" (~4pc) resolution will break up the emission into considerably smaller clumps. The linewidths will be reduced and we base our calculations on 5km/s velocity bins. 
For typical clumps of 1-2pc, the beam filling will thus be much higher than in our previous 2.3" resolution. In addition, much of the diffuse gas may be cleared out by the radiation from the AGN. This increases the beam filling factor even further for smaller beams. For a single clump, the beam filling difference will be of order 100, but given that there will be many clumps in each beam, we estimate a conservative 5 fold increase in surface brightness for the smaller beam, elevating the peak flux from 0.3K to 1.5K. With the requested rms of 0.2K, a S/N of 7 can therefore be achieved for HCN and 14 for HCO+ in this conservative estimate and for larger linewidths and filling factors the S/N can only increase.
 
Dynamic range considerations: The core of CenA has a flux density of ~6Jy at 1mm wavelengths. The continuum jet/core flux ratio is about of order a few, well within the typical ALMA dynamic range of ~100. The AGN is also adequate for self-calibration, which will increase the dynamic range
further. Although the emission lines are much fainter than the continuum, the self-calibrated noise from our Cycle 0 data shows thermal behavior and we expect that Cycle 3 data will be even better, given the much improved uv-coverage. In addition, we will subtract the continuum before mapping the line emission, which eliminates the influence of the strong continuum core almost completely.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We require two basebands for the continuum. The two spectral line basebands require ~1km/s resolution for the emission features, but also a very large bandwidth to potentially fit higher polynomials to determine an adequate baseline for the very bright source.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
