    <prp:abstract>The nearest radio galaxy by far is Centaurus A, a mere 3.8Mpc away. Its 5e7 Mo supermassive black hole (SMBH) is responsible for dramatic Mpc-scale radio jets and lobes. The AGN itself, however, has a relatively small sphere of direct gravitational influence and dominates the inner 1.4" (26pc), a scale which has now become accessible by ALMA. It is now possible to map the dense molecular, potentially star forming gas well within this unique region. We propose to perform this experiment using the HCO+ and HCN(3-2) transitions at a resolution of 0.2" (4pc). We will derive the rotation curve and extreme turbulent properties of the dense gas and compare it to more diffuse, hot and ionized phases. We will also determine the radiative sphere of influence, where X-rays largely control the state of the dense gas. Furthermore, we propose to push to the highest band 6 ALMA resolution of 0.03", similar to previous cm VLBI experiments. On this extreme scale, we will spatially resolve the complex molecular absorption of Cen A between the core and jet. This allows us to obtain size scales and projected distances for components that may directly emerge from clumps that feed the central engine. </prp:abstract>
